# Keeping Secrets 🔒

Not everything in a class should be visible to the world. We control visibility using **Access Specifiers**.

1.  **Public:** Accessible from anywhere.
2.  **Private:** Accessible **only** inside the class. (Default if not specified).
3.  **Protected:** Accessible inside the class and its child classes (Inheritance).

```cpp
class Box {
private:
    int secretKey; // Hidden
public:
    void open() { ... } // Visible
};
```

# Defining Behaviors 🏃

Functions inside a class are called **Methods** or **Member Functions**.

## 1. Inside Class Definition
```cpp
class Person {
    void walk() { cout << "Walking"; }
};
```

## 2. Outside Class Definition
Use the Scope Resolution Operator `::`.
```cpp
class Person {
    void walk(); // Prototype
};

void Person::walk() {
    cout << "Walking";
}
```

# The Birth of an Object 👶

A **Constructor** is a special method automatically called when an object is created.
- Same name as the class.
- No return type (not even void).

```cpp
class Car {
public:
    Car() {
        cout << "Car created!";
    }
};

int main() {
    Car myCar; // Prints "Car created!"
}
```

# Flavors of Constructors 🍦

1.  **Default Constructor:** No parameters.
2.  **Parameterized Constructor:** Takes arguments to initialize values.
3.  **Copy Constructor:** Creates a new object as a copy of an existing one.

```cpp
class Point {
    int x, y;
public:
    // Parameterized
    Point(int i, int j) {
        x = i;
        y = j;
    }
};

Point p1(10, 20);
```

# The End of the Line 💀

A **Destructor** is called when an object is destroyed (goes out of scope). 
- Same name as class but with `~`.
- Used to release resources (like closing files or freeing memory).

```cpp
~Car() {
    cout << "Car destroyed";
}
```

# Self Reference 🪞

Every object has a hidden pointer passed to all non-static member functions called `this`. It points to the object itself.

Useful when parameter names match member names.

```cpp
class Box {
    int length;
public:
    void setLength(int length) {
        this->length = length;
    }
};
```

# Sharing is Caring 🤝

**Static** members belong to the **class**, not any specific object. There is only one copy shared by all objects.

```cpp
class Counter {
public:
    static int count;
    Counter() { count++; }
};

// Initialize static member outside
int Counter::count = 0;
```
If you create 3 `Counter` objects, `count` will be 3.

